Portfolio design review - March 2026

What is actually working
- The site already has a clear personality. The pastel palette, rounded type, thick borders, and playful shapes make it recognizable.
- The blog page feels closest to polished because it is more restrained than the rest of the site.
- The project content is solid. The problem is mostly presentation, hierarchy, and editing discipline, not lack of substance.

Core diagnosis
- The site does not need more effects. It needs a stricter system.
- Right now multiple directions are competing at once: playful rounded typography, neo-brutalist borders and shadows, editorial whitespace, and toy-like motion.
- Each of those directions can work on its own, but together they make the site feel noisy instead of intentional.

Why Awwwards-level sites feel sharper
- They usually pick one visual metaphor and apply it everywhere.
- Their type system does more work, so they need fewer decorative tricks.
- Their motion is custom to the concept of the site, not a collection of recognizable hover effects.
- They remove more than they add. The polish is mostly in editing and consistency.

Main problems on the current site

1. Motion language is overloaded
- Home hero has a breathing loop.
- Buttons rotate and jump.
- Cards tilt in 3D.
- About cards wobble.
- Keywords shimmer.
- Contact button has its own jelly effect.
- Each interaction might be fine alone, but together they feel like a stack of effects rather than one motion system.

2. Typography has personality but not enough hierarchy
- Fredoka works for hero moments, but using the same expressive tone too broadly makes the site feel softer and less sharp.
- Too much uppercase reduces contrast between headings, nav items, tags, and buttons.
- Body text is a bit small and muted in a way that feels more casual than premium.
- The large pink text shadow on headings adds charm, but it also reduces crispness.

3. Too many colors carry equal weight
- The palette itself is not bad.
- The problem is that pink, mint, blue, yellow, and lavender all appear as active UI surfaces across the site.
- When every accent color gets to be loud, nothing feels primary.

4. Elevation is too loud everywhere
- Thick border plus hard shadow appears on hero card, nav, cards, buttons, and popovers.
- Because everything uses the same visual volume, the site has weak emphasis.
- Premium-feeling interfaces usually define only a few elevation levels and use them consistently.

5. The design system has drifted in code
- There are still older tokens and mismatched style ideas in the CSS.
- That usually means the visual system is no longer governed by a clean set of rules.
- Cleaning the system will make future design decisions easier.

What to do next

1. Lock the site structure
- Keep home as a single-page introduction.
- Keep the blog as a separate page and link to it from nav and footer only.
- Use the homepage as the front door: fast scan first, depth second.
- Keep long-form writing, archive browsing, and extra detail off the homepage.

2. Lock the creative direction
- Chosen direction: editorial research notebook / soft brutalist systems lab.
- Use one visual metaphor consistently: annotated cards, modular panels, system diagrams, orbital paths, data notes.
- The page should feel analytical, warm, and authored, not playful for its own sake.
- Awwwards-level here should mean one strong concept, crisp typography, and controlled motion, not more effects.

3. Define the job of the homepage
- In under 20 seconds, communicate who Vedant is, what field he fits into, and which projects matter most.
- Make Computer Engineering, AI, simulation, systems thinking, and tooling visible immediately.
- Highlight 4 to 6 strongest projects only.
- Give clear paths to GitHub, resume, blog, and LinkedIn.

4. Finish typography pass
- Use one display font and one body / UI font.
- Keep expressive typography for hero and section headings only.
- Remove broad uppercase styling from nav, buttons, tags, and metadata.
- Build a sharper hierarchy: hero, section title, card title, body, meta.
- Reduce decorative text shadows and improve body-text clarity.

5. Spacing and layout cleanup
- Normalize vertical rhythm between section headings, leads, grids, and footers.
- Tighten hero, card, and container spacing across home, about, toolbox, and blog.
- Make mobile spacing less jumpy across stacked sections.
- Move away from the centered-card-in-empty-space composition.
- Use stronger negative space, asymmetry, and full-page composition.

6. Remove at least half of the current animations
- Keep one reveal system.
- Keep one hover response system.
- Remove the hero breathing loop, button rotation, card wobble, keyword shimmer, and jelly hover.
- Motion should support the structure of the page, not compete with it.

7. Make motion specific to the site concept
- Generic magnetic buttons and 3D tilt feel borrowed.
- Interactions should feel tied to systems, AI, and research.
- Think in terms of annotations, diagrams, notebooks, terminals, modular cards, and subtle path-drawing transitions.
- Section transitions should come from layered reveals, background shifts, and diagram-like movement rather than gimmicks.
- Add reduced-motion support from the start.

8. Reduce the active color hierarchy
- Use cream and ink as the base.
- Choose one main accent per page or section.
- Use the other colors as occasional punctuation, not dominant surfaces.
- Make sure one color clearly leads and the others support.

9. Simplify the elevation system
- Define only three states: flat, raised, focal.
- Small controls should not feel as loud as large cards.
- Use thicker shadows and borders only where emphasis is actually needed.
- Avoid giving nav, buttons, cards, and popovers the same visual volume.

10. Rework the home composition, not just the styling
- Build the homepage as a full narrative instead of a single centered component.
- Give the hero one dominant layout move and one signature visual idea.
- Make each section feel like a deliberate transition, not another block stacked below.
- Use the full page for creativity through composition, type scale, and rhythm rather than more decorative widgets.

Proposed homepage sections
1. Hero / identity
- One strong statement about who Vedant is.
- One short supporting paragraph.
- Two clear actions such as View Projects and Resume / About.

2. Selected work
- One featured project with a wide layout.
- Three to five supporting projects in a more dynamic grid.
- Each project should show problem, build, stack, and outcome or why it matters.

3. Focus pillars
- AI and ML.
- Simulation and visualization.
- Systems thinking / tooling.

4. Process / philosophy
- A short section explaining how projects begin, how ideas are tested, and what kind of work is exciting.

5. Proof / current interests
- GitHub signals, current explorations, preferred tools, or current technical interests.

6. Footer / next step
- GitHub, LinkedIn, resume, blog, and contact.
- Blog remains a separate destination.

Recommended visual direction
- Editorial research notebook
- Soft brutalist systems lab
- Warm computational atlas

That direction suggests
- cleaner typography
- fewer active colors
- more intentional whitespace
- fewer but better interactions
- motion that feels analytical, not playful for its own sake

Professional baseline features
- Sticky navigation with active section highlighting.
- Deep-linkable sections.
- Strong project cards with clear content hierarchy.
- Clear resume / GitHub / LinkedIn access.
- Mobile-first behavior that still feels designed.
- Performance pass for fonts, animation cost, and image weight.
- Accessibility pass for contrast, focus states, keyboard navigation, and reduced motion.

Practical rewrite order
1. Lock homepage structure and content hierarchy.
2. Audit and remove old motion and typography drift.
3. Expand design tokens for type, space, color, elevation, and motion.
4. Rebuild the homepage composition around one stronger concept.
5. Add a signature motion system and section transitions.
6. Polish mobile layout, accessibility, and performance.
7. Keep the blog separate and more restrained than the homepage.

Implementation map
- index.html: new single-page homepage structure.
- blog/index.html: separate writing destination, not part of homepage flow.
- css/base/variables.css: typography scale, spacing system, color roles, elevation, motion timings.
- css/components/hero.css: hero composition and identity section.
- css/components/cards.css: featured and supporting project cards.
- css/components/navbar.css: sticky navigation and active states.
- css/desktop/animations.css: reveal system and section transitions.
- js/landing.js: homepage-specific interactions.
- js/desktop/scroll-effects.js: scroll-linked transitions and active-section behavior.

Success criteria
- The page feels intentional within the first 10 seconds.
- HR can understand the profile without clicking multiple pages.
- Engineers can immediately identify technical depth and strongest projects.
- Motion feels custom to the site's idea instead of borrowed.
- Every section justifies its existence.
- No visual effect survives unless it supports the core concept.

Rule for future changes
- Before adding any visual effect, ask: does this belong to the site's core idea, or is it just another cool thing?
- If the answer is just another cool thing, cut it.